entry.title: Support cloneForBranch2 when Teeing default readable streams
entry.content:
This CL implements support for the cloneForBranch2 flag in the Streams

API standard. Previously, when teeing default readable streams, the

data was not cloned for the second branch, and hence the same chunk

object was used on both branches. However, this does not match the

spec[1].



This change updates this behavior to match the spec. This is also

useful for scenarios where both branches are to be consumed in a way

that they might interfere with each other i.e. transferring their

chunks.



[1] https://streams.spec.whatwg.org/#readable-stream-tee

entry.title: Symbolize android logcat on the gtest and instrumentation tests
entry.content:
This adds symbolization to the logcat using the android stack tool [1]

on the CQ, impacting gtest and instrumentation tests.

To minimize the impact on runtime, this performs the symbolization

using logcat_monitor's transform_func [2]. The implementation of

stack_symbolizer.py copies the deobfuscator. The use of the pool being

helpful for handling crashes/restarts, and not parallelizing the

processing.

This required to update the stack tool, which was not flushing its

output. Trying to work around that by not necessarily returning lines

in the transform_func led to jumbled logcats.



Alternatively, I tried to process the whole logcat after the tests'

completion, but that slowed significantly the tests, e.g.:

- content_browsertests almost doubled from a typical 230 minutes

(11 per shard) to around 430 minutes(20 per shard).

- android_browsertests from a typical 55 minutes to 70 minutes

Using the transform_func led to similar runtimes than without this

patch.



[1] crsrc.org/c/third_party/android_platform/development/scripts/stack

[2] https://crsrc.org/c/third_party/catapult/devil/devil/android/logcat_monitor.py;drc=dc3e9bf012e68f78efc07dff48cdc023fc130739;l=40

[3] https://luci-logdog.appspot.com/logs/chromium/android/swarming/logcats/6127afedb798ec11/+/logcat_logcat_4331566088169232177_shard18_20230323T142855-UTC_FA7961A07067

entry.content:
This is a reland of commit b3e1103abca5d0dffa1696e4019e0149bdd1a964



The original CL is in patch set 1, and the other patch sets contain the

fix and a regression test.



Original change's description:

> [profiles] OpenBrowserWindowForProfile() fails when profile is deleted

>

> OpenBrowserWindowForProfile() is supposed to not call its callback in

> case of failure.

> Howevere, if the profile or the browser is deleted, the callback is

> still called, with no indication to the user that the operation has

entry.title: Adding metrics for multi output model execution cases.
entry.content:
In this CL,

[RecordSegmentSelectionFailure] Adding metrics to record model execution

failure and success state. The following are updated in this CL:

1. Recorded when reading from prefs at startup: [CachedResultProvider]

- SelectionAvailableInProtoPrefs

- InvalidSelectionAvailableInProtoPrefs

This tells whether there is a valid/invalid result available in prefs

for the segment.



2. Recorded when checking if prefs requires update or not.

[CachedResultWriter]

- ProtoPrefsUpdateNotRequired

- ProtoPrefsUpdated

This tells whether pref is expired or not. And if it is expired, then

if it is updated.



3. Recorded to tell model execution state. [ResultRefreshManager]

4. Recorded to tell if segment doesn't supports MultiOutput.

- MultiOutputNotSupported



[RecordClassificationResultComputed] Adding metrics for recording model

execution results whenever computed, eithier by running a model, or

getting valid score from database.



[RecordClassificationResultUpdated] Only recorded when prefs is expired

and updated.



Reason to seperate "Computed" and "Switched" metrics recording in

seperate methods is:

Previously, "Switched" is only recorded when updating to prefs and it is

not recorded in an ondemand case. Whereas "Computed" was getting

recorded when prefs is updated and on demand model execution case. The

method seems complicated doing both. Also wanted to differentiate when

to record "Computed" and "Switched" metrics.

entry.title: [keepalive-migration] Add basic in-browser redirect logic
entry.content:
## Context



When a renderer is alive, a keepalive redirect request goes through a

series of checks & modifications scattering around 7 methods [1] before

calling `mojom::URLLoader::FollowRedirect()`. When the renderer dies,

redirect needs to be handled in browser.



## Changes



This CL adds logic to directly follow redirect in browser. It also

adds checks to verify safe target & Content-Security-Policy (CSP).



For CSP: `KeepAliveURLLoader` and

`KeepAliveURLLoaderFactory::FactoryContext` both maintain a refptr to

`content::PolicyContainerHost` to let `PolicyCcontainerHost` outlives

its RFHI.





[1]: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1ZzxMMBvpqn8VZBZKnb7Go8TWjnrGcXuLS_USwVVRUvY/edit#heading=h.6uwqtijf7dvd

entry.title: [MirrorSync] Fix use after free on SyncStatusTracker
entry.content:
The issue was caused by a combination of 3 bugs:



1. Instead of only setting ids to leaf nodes, ids were set to all

nodes inserted to the trie to insert the desired path;



2. The case where a existing node is overriden with a new id

wasn't being handle at all (likely to happen during file dances);



3. The id of a node was not being reset to 0 (invalid stable_id)

when its corresponding path was detected to have been moved.



The combination of those 3 bugs could lead to a scenario exemplified

by the newly added unit test where, in summary, a series of operations

would lead to an entry in id_to_leaf_ pointing to a node that had

already been deleted.
